article.description: Pierson (25 points, 11 rebounds) makes huge return top Big 12 play
article.headline: Lady Raiders have no trouble with A&M
article.linkText: Pierson (25 points, 11 rebounds) makes huge return top Big 12 play
article.story:
COLLEGE STATION, Texas (AP) -- Plenette Pierson, Texas Tech's only senior starter, left little doubt Wednesday she is back as a dominant force in the Big 12.

She posted 25 points and 11 rebounds in leading the eighth-ranked Lady Raiders to a 77-56 victory over Texas A&M in the conference opener for both.

"It felt good to get back to playing in Big 12 Conference play again, especially after taking a year off,'' Pierson said.

The game was her first conference game since the 2000-2001 season. She sat out almost all of last season for undisclosed disciplinary reasons.

Pierson missed her first two shots. But with Tech holding a 7-6 lead, the senior forward scored the Red Raiders' next 10 points and led the team on a 15-4 run.

"She did a good job controlling the game for us in the beginning,'' Tech coach Marsha Sharp said. "There's no question we want to run our offense through her.''

Texas Tech (12-1) took a 41-21 lead at halftime, helped by Pierson's 17 points. Jia Perkins added 20 points and seven rebounds for Tech.

The nation's steal leader, Toccara Williams, had five of A&M's 15 swipes to move into second place all-time in Big 12 history. She also posted 10 points and five assists.

Texas A&M (7-5) lost its third straight game as Tech controlled the rebounds 52-28.

Lynn Classen led four Aggies in double figures with 13 points. Natasha Summerville added 12 points and 10 rebounds coming off the bench for A&M.

The Lady Raiders scored 21 second-chance points off of 25 offensive rebounds.

"We really went to the boards strong. It was the difference in the game for us,'' Sharp said.

A&M coach Peggie Gillom agreed.

"If you take away the rebounding it's a different ballgame,'' he said. "But I can't take anything away from Texas Tech, they're a great team.''

The Aggies were without their leading rebounder, senior forward
Kim Moore, who did not play. Gillom announced after the game that
Moore probably will miss the remainder of the season. Moore is
second in the conference in rebounds, averaging 9.1 per game, and
also is A&M's second-leading scorer at 12.7 points per game.

Gillom did not announce the reason for Moore's absence, but said
the coaching staff will meet with team doctors on Monday and
discuss Moore's options.

Texas Tech made fewer than half its free throws.

"I don't think we can be 10-for-22 from the line and still win
on the road very often,'' Sharp said.
